Bulk RNA

Morettini Francesco

2022-02-28

Introduction

In this Markdown we have an analysis of Bulk RNA-seq data, in particular we have 9 samples coming from 3 different tissues. For each of them three different samples were selected and analysed:

  • liver (SRR1324412, SRR1100991, SRR1349479)
  • kidney (SRR1486080, SRR1490658, SRR1325483)
  • heart (SRR606939, SRR1468613, SRR815184)

The analysis is done using the available packages on Bioconductor and CRAN, in particular with EdgeR. This package implements a range of statistical methodology based on the negative binomial distributions which are used for the computation of differential expression of genes across the samples.

Libraries

These packagese are needed for different analysis, some of them are useful for the analysis like the mentioned edgeR, but also SummarizedExperiment and DESeq2. Then I have used tidyverse which is a collection of packages that include ggplot2, dplyr and others that are very useful for the manipulation of data. xlsx is used for the writing of table in excel format and biomaRt is a powerful tool that I have used for retrieving information of any kind on genes and many other things.

Stats table

This table will list some of the main statistics of our samples. With the build_table function I search for the number of short RNA genes, which are those shorter than 200bp, and the mitochondrial genes which are on the chromosome m (chrM). Genes which are both short and mitochondrial are counted as short only as indicated in question 1. Also I compute the percentage of reads that are found on those genes.

build_table <- function(X, tissue){
  tissue <- tissue
  columns <- colnames(X)
  rse <- as.data.frame(X@rowRanges)
  read_counts <- as.data.frame(assay(X))
  
  total_reads <- colSums(read_counts)
  
  short_genes <- rse %>% filter(bp_length < 200) 
  reads_short_genes <- colSums(read_counts[short_genes$gene_id, ])
  percentage_short_reads <- reads_short_genes/total_reads * 100
  
  new_rse <- filter(rse, bp_length >= 200)
  
  MT_genes <- new_rse %>% filter(seqnames == "chrM")
  reads_MT_genes <- colSums(read_counts[MT_genes$gene_id, ])
  percentage_MT_reads <- reads_MT_genes / total_reads * 100
  
  df <- data.frame(rep(tissue, 3), columns, rep(nrow(short_genes), 3), rep(nrow(MT_genes), 3), total_reads, 
                   reads_short_genes, percentage_short_reads, reads_MT_genes, percentage_MT_reads)
  colnames(df) <- c("Tissue", "Sample", "Number of short genes", "Number of MT genes", "Total reads",
                    "Number of reads on short RNAs", "Percentage of reads on short RNAs", "Number of reads on MT genes",
                    "Percentage of reads on MT genes")
  return(df)
}  

liver_table <- build_table(liver, "liver")
kidney_table <- build_table(kidney, "kidney")
heart_table <- build_table(heart, "heart")

stats_table <- rbind(liver_table, kidney_table, heart_table)

Preprocessing

Creation of the count table

For every sample we need to build a count table, from that we will be able to build a DGEList object that will be used for the analysis.

count_table <- function(X){
  rse <- as.data.frame(X@rowRanges)
  read_counts <- as.data.frame(assay(X))
  keep_genes <- rse %>% filter(bp_length >= 200 & seqnames != "chrM")
  
  counts_keep_genes <- read_counts[keep_genes$gene_id, ]
}

counts_table_liver <- count_table(liver)
counts_table_kidney <- count_table(kidney)

Filtering

In this step we want to filter out all the genes with no expression at all or low expression across the 9 samples. This is performed by the filterByExpr function which determines the genes with a sufficient number of counts to be retained for a statistical analysis. The computation also depends on the library size.

zero_count <- table(rowSums(edger_table$counts == 0) == 9)
keep_genes <- filterByExpr(edger_table, group = groups)
edger_table <- edger_table[keep_genes, , keep.lib.sizes = FALSE]
logcpm <- as.data.frame(cpm(edger_table, log = TRUE))

Here we can take a look at the base 2 logarithm of the counts per million, we can see that the median for each boxplot is pretty different, hence we need a normalization. The normalization indeed is our following step and we will use TMM. In different colors we can see the 3 tissues: liver kidney and heart.

Normalization

Once we have filtered for:

  • Short genes
  • Mitochondrial genes
  • Low or not expressed genes

We can now normalize the counts according to the TMM which is the standard method for edgeR. The result of this operation is a change in the normalization factors of our DGEList object. The product of those factors with the original library size give us the effective library size which is the one used in downstream analysis.

edger_table <- calcNormFactors(edger_table, method = "TMM")

RNA integrity number (RIN)

RNA integrity number is a score associated to each RNA sample. In particular is a 2D plot which is used to measure RNA integrity. The plot give us the distribution of the size of RNAs, and we want them to be still integer, so a good result would be to have 2 (3 if we consider 5s) clear peaks representing the rRNA subunits (18s, 28s). All other RNAs length should be random and for this reason we should not see any other peak. If other peaks appeared it means that our RNA is degraded and we are left with small pieces of RNA. The score, that goes from 1 (very bad) to 10 (very good), measure the goodness of the plot. This is not manually computed, but the number is the result of a machine learning algorithm trained with plots annotated by experts. We consider as a threshold for reliable results a RIN of 7. We can see in the plot that overall liver and heart scores are pretty good whereas the RIN value for the kidney samples is low.

RIN <- dplyr::select(sample_info, Sample, RIN)  
RIN$Tissue <- c(rep("Liver", 3), rep("Kidney", 3), rep("Heart", 3))

ggplot(RIN, aes(x = Sample, y = RIN, fill = Tissue)) + geom_col() +
  xlab("Samples") + ylab("RIN scores") + ggtitle("Barplot for the RIN score with threshold") + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold", colour = "brown"), axis.text = element_text(size = 6)) + 
  geom_hline(yintercept = 7, color = "red", size = 3) +
  scale_x_discrete(limits = RIN$Sample) + scale_fill_manual(values=c("blue", "green", "orange"))

Dimensionality reduction

Now that we have the normalized expression of genes in our samples we can plot them to see if samples of the same tissue are similar and if samples of different tissues are well separated. So ideally, since we have 3 tissues we expect to see our 9 samples divided in 3 well separated clusters. However, we have more than 20000 genes so to plot all of them we would need more than 20000 dimensions which obviously we cant visualize. To solve this problem we use dimensionality reduction techniques, in our specific case we have two options which are multi-dimensional scaling (MDS) and principal component analysis (PCA). With both of them we can project our data in a 2 dimensional space where the 2 axis are computed such that we preserve as much as possible the variance of our data; preserving the variance of the data means preserve the information that they have. MDS instead of expression use the fold ratio values among the three samples to compute the principal components. In the following plots we can see both MDS and PCA, the first plot use as labels the samples while the second one the tissues. On the axis we can see the percentage of variance, with respect to the old space, that the new components are able to explain.

It is easy to see that the tissues cluster very well, in fact we have high intra-cluster similarity and low inter-cluster similarity.

plotMDS(logcpm, labels = samples, col = rep(c("blue", "green", "orange"), each = 3), main = "MDS plot first 2 components")

plotMDS(logcpm, labels = tissue, gene.selection = "common", col = rep(c("blue", "green", "orange"), each = 3, main = "PCA first 2 components"))

Just for curiosity we can try to plot the same thing however not using the 2 principal components, we can see that we are still able to identify clusters using the first and the third principal component, but if we use for example the third and the fourth than we are not able anymore to distinguish between the tissues. This is due to the fact that those components are associated with no or little information as we can see from the percentage of variability explained.

plotMDS(logcpm, labels = samples, col = rep(c("blue", "green", "orange"), each = 3), dim.plot = c(1,3), main = "MDS components 1 and 3")

plotMDS(logcpm, labels = samples, col = rep(c("blue", "green", "orange"), each = 3), dim.plot = c(3,4), main = "MDS components 3 and 4")

Model fitting

Now we want to find which are the genes differentially expressed in our tissues. To do that we need to build a model which is a generalized linear model. The reason for which we are building this kind of model is that since we previously considered the Negative Binomial distribution we cant build a simple linear model because this is based on the assumption that data are normally distributed. Also we have the advantage that we can compare more than 2 conditions at the same time. So we build the model with the data that we have treated until now.

model_glm <- glmQLFit(edger_table, design_matrix)

Once we have build the model we can use it to test whether genes are differentially expressed between two samples. We will start by doing three different comparisons:

  • Liver vs Kidney
  • Liver vs Heart
  • Kidney vs Heart

To do those comparison we have to explicit the two tissues we are considering and for which one we are going to compute the up-regulated and down-regulated genes. Also, since we are considering more than 20000 genes in our analysis we will have to consider multiple test correction. We have many different options when it comes to this, some are more stringent than others, for example Bonferroni is the more stringent one, where all the p-values are corrected in the same way. This type of correction decrease the number of false positives, which is certainly good, however it increases a lot the number of false negatives; increasing too much the number of false negatives may not be what we want because we may loose many information. Also this type of correction is based on the assumption that tests are not correlated, however this is not the case. For those reasons Bonferroni is not used anymore. Other correction which are progressively less stringent are Bonferroni-Holm, Westfall and Young based on permutations and finally Benjamini Hochberg or false discovery rate (FDR) which is the one that we are going to use. As a threshold for considering a gene differentially expressed we will consider both the adjusted p-value, which should be lower than a certain threshold (usually 0.05 but 0.01 may work better) and also the log2fold change, for which the absolute value should be usually greater than 1. It will be smaller than -1 for down-regulated genes and greater than 1 for up-regulated.

We start by applying our model to the different couple of tissues and computing the adjusted p-values.

Liver_vs_Kidney <- glmQLFTest(model_glm, contrast = c(1,-1,0)) 
Liver_vs_Heart <- glmQLFTest(model_glm, contrast = c(1,0,-1))
Kidney_vs_Heart <- glmQLFTest(model_glm, contrast = c(0,1,-1))

FDR_Liver_vs_Kidney <- p.adjust(Liver_vs_Kidney$table$PValue, method = "BH")
FDR_Liver_vs_Heart <- p.adjust(Liver_vs_Heart$table$PValue, method = "BH")
FDR_Kidney_vs_Heart <- p.adjust(Kidney_vs_Heart$table$PValue, method = "BH")

Now we have to decide which thresholds to use in order to obtain meaningful results. In a first moment I have tried to use the canonical values: a level of significance of \(\alpha = 0.05\) for the adjusted p-values and an absolute value of 1 for the log2FC.

Liver vs Kidney:

summary(decideTests(Kidney_vs_Heart, lfc = 1))

## Down                    1596
## NotSig                 20440
## Up                      2094

Already here we can see that using those thresholds we obtain many differentially expressed genes. In general we would like to have around a thousands of DE genes, although there is not a precise rule. Continuing the pipeline with those parameters result in a poor functional enrichment analysis so I have decided to lower the thresholds using a more stringent value of \(\alpha = 0.01\) mantaining the same value for the log2FC.

Liver vs Kidney:

summary(decideTests(Liver_vs_Kidney, lfc = 1, p.value = 0.01))  
##        1*1_Liver -1*2_Kidney

Once we have computed the number of differentially expressed genes we can also find the using the function topTags. In this way we can obtain a dataframe in which we have all the DE genes with the associated adjusted p-value and the log2FC. Given the log2FC we can also say if they are up or down regulated. So we create three dataframes, one for each of the comparisons that we have done.

tags_LK <- topTags(Liver_vs_Kidney, n = 5000, adjust.method = "BH", sort.by = "PValue", p.value = 0.01)$table
tags_LH <- topTags(Liver_vs_Heart, n = 5000, adjust.method = "BH", sort.by = "PValue", p.value = 0.01)$table
tags_KH <- topTags(Kidney_vs_Heart, n = 5000, adjust.method = "BH", sort.by = "PValue", p.value = 0.01)$table
tags_LK$DE <- ifelse(tags_LK$logFC > 1, "Up", "Down")
tags_LH$DE <- ifelse(tags_LH$logFC > 1, "Up", "Down")
tags_KH$DE <- ifelse(tags_KH$logFC > 1, "Up", "Down")

As final step of this analysis we want to find the genes that are up-regulated or down-regulated in both the comparison with respect to the other 2 tissues. To do that we look for the genes that are found in both the previous dataframes for a certain tissue.

up_Liver <- merge(up_LK, up_LH, by = 0, all = FALSE)

Functional enrichment analysis

After having discovered the genes that are differentially expressed we want to perform a functional enrichment analysis on them. Basically we want to see if they are enriched for certain pathways. To do that we can use different software such as DAVID Enrichr and GSEA. To use them we have to provide those with a gene set, however, not all of them accept the ensembl gene ID but they should be provided with the gene symbols. In order to do that we can use biomart which is a project that provides access to many distributed research data. We can query biomart with our set of genes and it will return all the information that we want included the gene symbol. With this tool we can retrieve the majority of gene symbols, however not all of them since there is some disparity between the notations. In fact working with these lists of genes is easy to find duplicated ensembl gene id, or ensembl gene id that corresponds to multiple gene symbols or sometimes the gene id may be associated with an alias of the gene symbol. The query is done on homo sapiens gene ensembl dataset. Fianlly before querying our list of genes we have to remove the version from the gene ID which are the numbers after the dot. The function also produce a .txt file that can be used for the functional annotation analysis.

ensembl <- useEnsembl(biomart = "genes", dataset = "hsapiens_gene_ensembl")

retrieve_names <- function(genes, tissue){
  ensembl_ID <- genes$Row.names
  ensembl_ID <- gsub("\\..*", "", ensembl_ID)
  all_genes_ensg <- getBM(mart = ensembl,
                          attributes = c('hgnc_symbol', 'ensembl_gene_id', 'chromosome_name'),
                          filters = "ensembl_gene_id",
                          values = ensembl_ID)
  all_genes_ensg <- all_genes_ensg[complete.cases(all_genes_ensg), ]
  all_genes_ensg <- all_genes_ensg[!(is.na(all_genes_ensg$hgnc_symbol) | all_genes_ensg$hgnc_symbol == ""), ]
  write.table(all_genes_ensg$hgnc_symbol, file = paste0("HGNC_symbol_for_DE_genes_", tissue, ".txt"), quote = FALSE,
              col.names = FALSE, row.names = FALSE)
  return(all_genes_ensg)
}


gene_names_up_liver <- retrieve_names(up_Liver, "Liver")
gene_names_up_kidney <- retrieve_names(up_Kidney, "Kidney")
gene_names_up_heart <- retrieve_names(up_Heart, "Heart")

Up regulated gene

We now have to find the gene which is up regulated in the comparison between Liver and Kidney with the lower FDR. Then we want it to be found also in the comparison between Liver and Heart. To do that we use a while a loop that search our gene. Once we have find it we have to check if it has two alternative transcripts on the GENCODE v25 track of the Genome Browser.

cond = TRUE
while (cond){
  #Select the best gene
  best_gene <- rownames(tags_LK[which.min(tags_LK[tags_LH$logFC < -1,]$FDR),])
  #If it is present also in tags_LH will return TRUE and stop the loop
  cond <- best_gene %notin% rownames(tags_LH)
  #However if it is present but the logFC is smaller than -1 it means is downregulated so we don't want him
  if (tags_LH[best_gene, ]$logFC <= -1){
    cond == TRUE
  }
  #If the gene is not present in tags_LH remove it from tags_LK so to select the next one
  tags_LK <- tags_LK %>% filter(row.names(tags_LK) %notin% best_gene)
}

Before looking on the genome browser we can also search on biomart how many transcripts are found and which is its position on the genome. As before we have to remove the part that comes after the dot in the ensembl gene id.

best_gene_ens_id <- gsub("\\..*", "", best_gene)

                        attributes = c('ensembl_gene_id', 'ensembl_transcript_id', 'start_position', 'chromosome_name'),

RPKM

Finally we compute the RPKM for the previous gene. To do that we need to retrieve all the information which are necessary. Those are the gene length, which is the sum of bp that are constituting an exon, this will be retrieved again with biomart. Than we need the read count associated with the gene and the overall number of reads used for quantification.

best_gene_data <- getBM(mart = ensembl,
                         attributes = c('ensembl_gene_id', 'exon_chrom_start', 'exon_chrom_end', 'ensembl_transcript_id'),
                         filters = "ensembl_gene_id",
                         values = best_gene_ens_id)

best_gene_table <- filter(best_gene_data, ensembl_transcript_id == "ENST00000359481")
best_gene_table$exon_lenght <- best_gene_table$exon_chrom_end - best_gene_table$exon_chrom_start
gene_length <- sum(best_gene_table$exon_lenght)
reads <- as.data.frame(edger_table$samples)$lib.size
counts <- as.data.frame(edger_table$counts)
counts_best_gene <- counts %>% filter(row.names(counts) %in% best_gene)

RPKM <- counts_best_gene * 1000 * 1000000/(reads * gene_length)
